column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'US Politics', 'Security and Conflict']

In the context of the sheer complexity of immigration issues, this issue is, on the surface, least complex. It has the deep support of Trump's populace base and will draw support from the great majority of Congressional Republicans and a considerable number of conservative Democrats. Phrased this way, it skirts the less obvious intent of putting a ban on the entry of all Muslims, which would invite serious opposition, particularly on Constitutional grounds. I believe that there is a greater chance of perceiving that the latter goal (banning all Muslims) could be largely accomplished in a practical way by making it less obvious to the eye. Wording of this sort on any legislation would go a long way toward fulfilling that goal; it will not fool many opponents, however, and therefore will promote fierce argument. Nevertheless I believe such wording gives it a good chance of meeting the April 30th deadline In light of the recent poorly designed executive order and the subsequent uproar it provoked, pivotal to whether this kind of action can effectively been implemented a second time will depend on how well the President's immediate actions in effecting a revised executive order as well as whether Supreme Court Justice Neil Gorsuch faces a Democratic filibuster slowing down his confirmation.
